{"id": 2113732, "abstract": "We address the problem of simulating efficiently from the posterior distribution over the parameters of a particular class of nonlinear regression models using a Langevin-Metropolis sampler. It is shown that as the number N of parameters increases, the proposal variance must scale as N{-1/3} in order to converge to a diffusion. This generalizes previous results of Roberts and Rosenthal [J. R. Stat. Soc. Ser. B Stat. Methodol. 60 (1998) 255-268] for the i.i.d. case, showing the robustness of their analysis.", "cluster": "5", "citations": [233967527, 232718818, 232276216, 222298844, 1771219, 277289463, 24111924, 227719006, 45866217, 45907693], "references": [233432656, 227425151, 38362523, 38361537, 29770198, 2583743, 227672958, 38326865, 2358401, 233971671], "authors": ["Laird Arnault Breyer", "Mauro Piccioni", "Sergio Scarlatti"], "title": "Optimal Scaling of Mala for Nonlinear Regression"}